WEBVTT

00:02.728 --> 00:04.378
("Weird Al" Yankovic sings)

00:06.398 --> 00:08.215
(playing<i> The Simpsons</i> theme)

00:21.096 --> 00:23.004
-(cheering)
-So weird.

00:23.098 --> 00:25.691
-So, can I stay for dinner?
-No.

00:27.194 --> 00:29.403
(accordion resumes
playing theme)

00:30.680 --> 00:32.656
(Yankovic vocalizes)

00:37.596 --> 00:39.521
<i> NARRATOR: And they'll toot</i>
<i> their horn-honkers</i>

00:39.615 --> 00:41.356
<i> to proclaim its renown.</i>

00:41.375 --> 00:43.542
<i> But there's one tale</i>
<i> the townsfolk</i>

00:43.693 --> 00:45.285
<i> won't brag of or bray.</i>

00:45.437 --> 00:47.604
<i> It's what happened</i>
<i> on Springfield's</i>

00:47.623 --> 00:50.290
<i> dum-dummiest day.</i>

00:50.442 --> 00:52.384
(snoring)

00:56.706 --> 00:59.207
Ach! The grid is overloaded.

00:59.226 --> 01:03.187
But who and how and where
and what for?

01:03.972 --> 01:05.806
Ach! Eek!

01:05.900 --> 01:06.881
Loch! Ewan!

01:06.975 --> 01:08.292
Crivvens!

01:08.385 --> 01:10.294
-(cackling)
-My precious grid.

01:10.312 --> 01:13.363
One more daft device
and she'll explode.

01:14.300 --> 01:18.118
No!

01:23.492 --> 01:25.275
(coughing)

01:26.736 --> 01:29.904
Dear God, to mitigate the smell
of emulsified eggs and vinegar,

01:29.998 --> 01:32.073
we'll have to close the school
for weeks.

01:32.167 --> 01:33.741
-(cheering, whooping)
-Yay!
-Awesome.

01:33.836 --> 01:35.094
-That's great!
-All right!

01:35.245 --> 01:36.428
You clearly misheard me.

01:36.580 --> 01:38.931
I said the school
will be closed.

01:39.082 --> 01:42.101
And we said,
"woo-hoo," "awesome,"

01:42.328 --> 01:44.344
and "that's great."

01:44.496 --> 01:46.346
<i> ANNOUNCER: You're watching</i>
SportsCenter Classic.

01:46.440 --> 01:50.275
<i> Stay tuned for more exciting</i>
<i> baseball scores from 1986.</i>

01:50.427 --> 01:52.002
1986.

01:52.020 --> 01:54.004
I was two years old then.

01:54.022 --> 01:55.839
Or was I 30?

01:55.932 --> 01:57.265
<i> COMMERCIAL ANNOUNCER:</i>
<i>Stressed out from IRS troubles?</i>

01:57.284 --> 01:58.617
<i> Irreversible Mortgage?</i>

01:58.768 --> 02:01.102
<i> Chockaholic's Foot,</i>
<i> formerly known as diabetes?</i>

02:01.271 --> 02:03.196
<i> I can make</i>
<i> those stresses disappear</i>

02:03.349 --> 02:04.698
<i> like a shattered backboard.</i>

02:04.850 --> 02:07.701
<i> (gasps) Late-night commercial</i>
<i> legend Shaquille O'Neal?</i>

02:07.795 --> 02:09.444
<i> You need Tightie Mighties,</i>

02:09.463 --> 02:11.188
<i> the compression underwear</i>
<i> with the proven</i>

02:11.281 --> 02:14.115
<i> nerve-soothing properties</i>
<i> of copper wire.</i>

02:14.135 --> 02:15.859
<i> Operators are standing by.</i>

02:15.952 --> 02:17.469
<i> It's a slam dunk.</i>

02:17.621 --> 02:20.180
(gasps)
That's the best kind of dunk.

02:21.049 --> 02:22.699
For crying out loud.

02:22.718 --> 02:24.143
I said no more buying junk

02:24.370 --> 02:26.870
from late-night ads
on basic cable.

02:26.889 --> 02:28.538
Look at all this stuff.

02:28.632 --> 02:30.223
Unkinkable garden hoses,

02:30.317 --> 02:31.799
squatty potties.

02:31.877 --> 02:35.303
Why do you need the world's
most powerful flashlight?

02:35.397 --> 02:36.546
Aah!

02:36.565 --> 02:38.973
-It has the most lumens.
-(grunts)

02:39.067 --> 02:42.310
These late-night cable hucksters
are getting rich

02:42.404 --> 02:45.164
off gullible people like you.

02:45.315 --> 02:47.057
Oh, no, you're right.

02:47.226 --> 02:49.893
I'm as stupid as the guy
who couldn't make spaghetti

02:49.986 --> 02:52.838
before he bought
the Spaghetti Samurai.

02:53.065 --> 02:53.914
(snoring)

02:54.066 --> 02:55.065
LISA:
Dad, wake up.

02:55.158 --> 02:56.842
Get up, dummy.

02:56.993 --> 02:57.901
(stammers) Huh?

02:57.994 --> 02:59.085
This is our classroom

02:59.238 --> 03:01.663
until our school
doesn't smell like eggs.

03:01.682 --> 03:04.533
(shudders)
Homeschooling.

03:04.593 --> 03:07.561
Every half-assed parent's
nightmare.

03:12.342 --> 03:14.151
Oh...

03:17.198 --> 03:19.514
First law of robotics:

03:19.533 --> 03:21.516
you suck.

03:21.535 --> 03:24.611
Okay, so, if I have
$500 in the bank,

03:24.705 --> 03:27.372
and your mother wants to take
two-thirds of it

03:27.524 --> 03:30.042
to buy a purse,
when her old purse

03:30.193 --> 03:31.859
is just fine...

03:31.879 --> 03:34.104
You?
$500 in the bank?

03:34.122 --> 03:36.048
What are you teaching him,
science fiction?

03:36.199 --> 03:39.609
No, real fiction, Luann.
It's real fiction.

03:39.703 --> 03:41.611
(bell clangs)

03:41.705 --> 03:43.037
Okay, class,

03:43.131 --> 03:46.132
it's time for our unit
on Springfield history.

03:46.285 --> 03:48.618
Ooh, more
pumpkin stickers for me.

03:48.712 --> 03:52.122
I still got room for one more
between my toes.

03:52.140 --> 03:54.307
(shuddering laugh)

03:54.401 --> 03:55.567
"Chapter four:

03:55.719 --> 03:57.486
a Great Endeavor."

03:59.055 --> 04:00.647
Today, we christen

04:00.799 --> 04:02.983
the Great Springfield Gazebo,

04:03.151 --> 04:05.577
wherein romance-minded gentlemen

04:05.729 --> 04:07.579
the world over may come

04:07.731 --> 04:09.081
to court their intendeds.

04:09.232 --> 04:11.308
This grand new structure

04:11.326 --> 04:13.085
shall make Springfield

04:13.236 --> 04:16.213
the woo-pitching capital
of America.

04:20.168 --> 04:24.004
Gentlemen, start your ukuleles.

04:24.098 --> 04:26.932
GENTLEMEN:
♪<i> I will always</i> ♪

04:27.083 --> 04:29.009
♪<i> Be true</i> ♪

04:29.161 --> 04:31.419
♪<i> Spend my days</i> ♪

04:31.438 --> 04:33.680
♪<i> Pitching woo</i> ♪

04:33.832 --> 04:35.107
♪<i> To you...</i> ♪

04:35.258 --> 04:37.442
(ladies giggling, swooning)

04:37.594 --> 04:38.610
Oh, God, oh, dear God, um,

04:38.762 --> 04:40.946
we didn't account
for the harmonic frequency

04:41.173 --> 04:44.116
of the wooing.
It's too romantic!

04:44.267 --> 04:46.601
Please, I beg you,
stop making love

04:46.620 --> 04:49.437
in the old-timey sense
as we understand it today.

04:49.515 --> 04:51.790
♪<i> Not a moment I'll rue</i> ♪

04:51.941 --> 04:53.792
♪<i> As I serenade you</i> ♪

04:54.019 --> 04:56.186
♪<i> My sweet</i> ♪

04:56.204 --> 05:00.173
♪<i> Mary Lou.</i> ♪

05:02.970 --> 05:04.970
<i> MARGE:</i>
<i> Glory turned to fiasco</i>

05:05.121 --> 05:07.789
<i> for the disgraced</i>
<i> Mayor of Springfield,</i>

05:07.883 --> 05:09.808
<i> Eustace Van Houten.</i>

05:09.959 --> 05:11.793
(coughs)

05:11.812 --> 05:14.204
Aw, soup crackers.

05:14.297 --> 05:16.706
-MAN 1: Charlatan!
-MAN 2: Mountebank!

05:16.800 --> 05:18.299
WOMAN:
Dunderhead!

05:18.319 --> 05:21.302
Dad, was he
one of our relatives?

05:21.322 --> 05:24.972
Yeah, he was your
great-great-grandfather.

05:25.141 --> 05:27.233
Not so great, I guess.

05:27.386 --> 05:30.737
So, the Van Houtens
have always been losers.

05:30.831 --> 05:33.481
Not true, son.
Hey, your granddad

05:33.500 --> 05:36.484
once prepared a Caesar salad
for Dean Martin,

05:36.578 --> 05:38.152
right at the table.
(chuckles)

05:38.172 --> 05:41.247
Fine, Dad.
I'm gonna go to Phys Ed.

05:41.400 --> 05:44.092
We're doing swimming today.

05:49.758 --> 05:50.849
Mm...

05:51.000 --> 05:52.092
<i> (sighs)</i>

05:52.244 --> 05:53.577
My life is hard enough,

05:53.595 --> 05:56.613
now I find out that the school
is teaching my son

05:56.615 --> 05:59.766
that every one of his ancestors
is a loser.

05:59.918 --> 06:01.509
(groans)

06:01.528 --> 06:04.696
I bought so many
stupid useless products.

06:04.923 --> 06:06.940
Pretzel Straightener,
Face Bidet,

06:07.034 --> 06:09.368
-Spray-on Music.
-(rattles)

06:09.595 --> 06:11.536
<i> (The Price is Right</i>
losing horns playing)

06:14.266 --> 06:16.282
I'm financially ruined,

06:16.359 --> 06:18.210
and it's all his fault.

06:18.361 --> 06:21.287
<i> Now your belly button can live</i>
<i> the lint-free lifestyle</i>

06:21.440 --> 06:23.048
<i> with the Navel Vac.</i>

06:23.125 --> 06:25.032
<i> And she'll like it, too.</i>

06:25.085 --> 06:26.292
She didn't.

06:26.445 --> 06:28.536
Shaq, you suckered me again.

06:28.555 --> 06:31.556
Hey, hey, hey.
I will not have you badmouthing

06:31.708 --> 06:33.116
Shaquille Rashaun O'Neal.

06:33.118 --> 06:34.559
Four-time NBA champ,

06:34.786 --> 06:36.453
rapper, actor, sheriff,

06:36.471 --> 06:39.046
restaurateur,
black belt in Shaq-Fu,

06:39.066 --> 06:40.807
Shaq belt in kung fu,

06:40.959 --> 06:42.642
and now
the Big Aristotle dominates

06:42.794 --> 06:43.810
the late-night airwaves.

06:43.962 --> 06:46.129
He is living proof that anybody

06:46.148 --> 06:47.631
can make their dreams come true.

06:47.649 --> 06:51.317
You're right. If I could just
think of one thing to sell

06:51.394 --> 06:54.061
that nobody needs
and everybody wants,

06:54.081 --> 06:55.396
I could pay off my bills

06:55.416 --> 06:58.141
and be a super-success
like Shaq.

06:58.234 --> 07:00.326
And you, Big Milhouse,
stop whining.

07:00.479 --> 07:02.236
Somebody calls
your family a loser,

07:02.256 --> 07:03.980
you stand up for yourself.

07:03.999 --> 07:05.815
I will.

07:05.834 --> 07:07.843
(inspirational music playing)

07:09.337 --> 07:12.172
<i> SKINNER:</i>
<i> On behalf of the school board,</i>
<i> I declare</i>

07:12.324 --> 07:14.340
school is officially reopened.

07:14.493 --> 07:18.103
Let the free childcare and
intermittent learning resume.

07:18.330 --> 07:20.772
I'm here to officially protest
the teaching

07:20.924 --> 07:23.442
of the Great Springfield
Gazebo Disaster.

07:23.518 --> 07:25.852
It makes our children
hate our town

07:25.946 --> 07:27.854
and me hate myself.

07:27.948 --> 07:29.355
The Gazebo Disaster?

07:29.432 --> 07:32.525
But we plan to tread water
on that unit for months.

07:32.602 --> 07:33.843
We're doing two weeks

07:33.862 --> 07:36.696
on the substandard
metal bracing alone.

07:36.848 --> 07:37.864
Not anymore.

07:37.958 --> 07:39.699
I demand that you ban

07:39.793 --> 07:42.368
Critical Brace Theory now.

07:42.463 --> 07:44.871
Sir, we're not changing
our curriculum

07:45.023 --> 07:47.707
just to shore up
the wet cardboard lean-to

07:47.859 --> 07:50.026
that is your family self-esteem.

07:50.045 --> 07:51.878
Then you leave me one choice.

07:52.030 --> 07:54.030
Until you meet my demands,

07:54.049 --> 07:57.200
I'm going to play this trumpet,
on which

07:57.293 --> 08:00.537
I have no formal training.

08:00.555 --> 08:02.129
(dissonant playing)

08:02.224 --> 08:04.632
-Aah!
-Mr. Van Houten, if we,

08:04.726 --> 08:05.892
uh, if we could just...

08:06.044 --> 08:08.561
Look, there's no need
for brass instruments.

08:08.714 --> 08:11.548
For 30 years,
we've been pleading with parents

08:11.566 --> 08:13.049
to get more involved.

08:13.068 --> 08:15.494
-What the hell were we thinking?
-(Marge grumbles)

08:21.727 --> 08:23.076
I know Kirk is angry,

08:23.228 --> 08:24.744
but I'm a little worried
this meeting

08:24.896 --> 08:26.654
will go off the rails.

08:26.823 --> 08:28.507
Marge, stop saying things.

08:28.658 --> 08:30.750
I'm trying to think
of an amazing product

08:30.902 --> 08:32.569
that can get us out of debt.

08:32.662 --> 08:34.404
Uh... um...

08:34.422 --> 08:36.998
Handgun Underpants?
Mm, no.

08:37.017 --> 08:38.833
Uh, Bucket in a Box?

08:38.852 --> 08:41.002
Spoon 2.0?
Steak Bedazzler?

08:41.021 --> 08:42.262
Oh...

08:42.414 --> 08:44.505
(clears throat)
Yes, we are all here

08:44.583 --> 08:47.842
because one lone parent
raised an issue

08:47.936 --> 08:50.103
that he thinks
is worth me missing

08:50.255 --> 08:52.013
the new<i> Equalizer</i> starring

08:52.032 --> 08:53.848
that delightful Queen Latifah.

08:53.942 --> 08:56.350
Kirk!
You, regrettably,

08:56.444 --> 08:57.761
have the floor.

08:57.929 --> 08:59.220
We need to stop teaching

08:59.222 --> 09:03.024
that my great-grandfather's
gazebo was a disaster.

09:03.043 --> 09:05.710
But it was,
and it was his fault.

09:05.937 --> 09:09.196
His dying words were, "My bad."

09:09.216 --> 09:10.957
So?
Why can't our kids learn

09:11.034 --> 09:13.034
about things that make
our town proud?

09:13.128 --> 09:15.111
Like, how if you want
to make a right on red,

09:15.130 --> 09:16.963
it's usually not a problem.

09:17.115 --> 09:19.874
Why do we have to focus
on the bad stuff?

09:19.893 --> 09:22.209
(indistinct chatter)

09:22.229 --> 09:24.954
We completely disagree.

09:25.123 --> 09:28.808
It's essential that all of
Springfield's darkest chapters

09:28.960 --> 09:30.902
be taught: the monorail,

09:31.129 --> 09:32.312
Lady Gaga's visit,

09:32.464 --> 09:34.406
and the gazebo collapse.

09:34.557 --> 09:37.242
If our kids aren't made to feel
ashamed of the past,

09:37.393 --> 09:40.987
how will they learn
to be ashamed of the future?

09:41.139 --> 09:41.988
(indistinct chatter)

09:42.140 --> 09:43.397
Look at my son.

09:43.491 --> 09:45.900
You think he needs
to feel worse about himself

09:45.919 --> 09:48.828
than he already clearly does?
(grunts)

09:48.980 --> 09:51.648
You are doing this to him!

09:51.666 --> 09:53.650
(cheering)

09:53.743 --> 09:55.835
I agree with the bald lady.

09:55.912 --> 09:57.929
Why does history
have to be hurtful?

09:58.081 --> 09:59.598
Every book about World War II

09:59.825 --> 10:01.933
makes the Germans the bad guys.

10:02.160 --> 10:03.935
Stop teaching facts!

10:04.087 --> 10:05.937
Historical guilt is everything.

10:06.106 --> 10:09.332
You snowflakes
are hurting our feelings.

10:09.425 --> 10:11.610
Those who cannot
remember the past

10:11.761 --> 10:13.519
are condemned to repeat it.

10:13.614 --> 10:16.615
On the other hand, those
who cannot remember the past

10:16.766 --> 10:18.933
are condemned to repeat it.

10:19.027 --> 10:21.435
People, people, people!
People.

10:21.455 --> 10:24.030
We are not
going to settle this tonight.

10:24.182 --> 10:25.957
I move that we end this meeting

10:26.109 --> 10:28.109
with everyone
angry and dissatisfied.

10:28.128 --> 10:29.461
All in favor?

10:29.612 --> 10:30.962
ALL:
Boo!

10:31.189 --> 10:33.131
Wonderful.
It's unanimous.

10:33.324 --> 10:33.965
Mm.

10:34.192 --> 10:36.042
Dad, I know this
is a weird thing

10:36.194 --> 10:38.136
for a son to say to his father,

10:38.363 --> 10:40.121
but I'm proud of you.

10:40.215 --> 10:42.715
You actually convinced people.

10:42.809 --> 10:44.033
I did?

10:44.202 --> 10:45.885
You the man, Kirk.

10:45.979 --> 10:49.038
-I am?
-No, you the my man.

10:49.132 --> 10:50.540
This marriage may have

10:50.558 --> 10:53.068
just got un-sexless.

10:54.303 --> 10:56.655
It's so sad when people
can't get along.

10:56.806 --> 10:58.973
It causes upsetment.

10:58.992 --> 11:01.142
Marge, people need to disagree

11:01.161 --> 11:02.810
and have their voice
shouted over.

11:02.829 --> 11:05.997
That's what democracy was.
Remember that?

11:06.107 --> 11:09.225
But everyone in this country
is so divided.

11:09.244 --> 11:12.420
Where will all
this hostility lead?

11:13.565 --> 11:15.156
I'll tell you
where it leads, Homer.

11:15.175 --> 11:18.093
Straight to the bank--
the money bank.

11:19.179 --> 11:20.403
-(backboard clanks)
-This is the idea

11:20.422 --> 11:22.663
-you've been looking for.
-It is?

11:22.683 --> 11:25.408
What's the one thing
every American has in common?

11:25.427 --> 11:28.019
(gasps)
They're furious all the time

11:28.171 --> 11:29.746
about everything.

11:29.839 --> 11:31.172
Ex-Shaq-ly.

11:31.266 --> 11:34.025
Now, think-- how can you
make money from that?

11:34.177 --> 11:38.029
I know just what to do.

11:38.181 --> 11:39.513
<i> Hurry up, everyone!</i>

11:39.533 --> 11:41.682
My thing's coming on.

11:41.776 --> 11:44.594
The thing
I never told you about.

11:44.687 --> 11:46.538
<i> Are you full of anger</i>
<i> at your kids' school</i>

11:46.765 --> 11:47.931
<i> or at life in general?</i>

11:48.024 --> 11:49.356
<i> You know it.</i>

11:49.451 --> 11:51.784
<i> Well, now you can express</i>
<i> your scalding hot rage</i>

11:51.937 --> 11:53.269
<i> with the light-up "Me-Shirt."</i>

11:53.438 --> 11:57.198
<i> Why, that's so obnoxious.</i>
<i> I love it.</i>

11:57.292 --> 11:59.609
<i> The Me-Shirt has dozens</i>
<i> of snappy slogans</i>

11:59.627 --> 12:01.277
<i> tailor-made</i>
<i> for your recently-acquired</i>

12:01.296 --> 12:03.279
<i> but deeply-held views.</i>

12:03.298 --> 12:05.557
<i> "Never Remember,"</i>
<i> "The Truth Will Make You Sad,"</i>

12:05.708 --> 12:08.284
<i> and "Don't Teach on Me."</i>

12:08.303 --> 12:10.803
<i> Plus, the copper-infused fiber</i>
<i> that powers the lights</i>

12:10.956 --> 12:12.546
<i> gives you more energy</i>

12:12.624 --> 12:15.049
<i> and pushes all the blood</i>
<i> to your face.</i>

12:15.068 --> 12:19.053
<i>I'll never look not angry again.</i>

12:19.147 --> 12:21.555
Wow, Dad, way to milk
the rage-bucks

12:21.575 --> 12:22.982
out of the red hat crowd.

12:23.134 --> 12:25.134
Well, I found it appalling.

12:25.136 --> 12:27.912
We have a shirt for you, too.

12:28.915 --> 12:30.990
<i> Oh, hi there.</i>
<i> You caught me wearing</i>

12:31.067 --> 12:32.809
<i>my carbon-neutral light-up shirt</i>

12:32.827 --> 12:34.160
<i> with progressive slogans like:</i>

12:34.312 --> 12:35.903
<i> "Shame On Us," "I Know Best,"</i>

12:35.922 --> 12:40.425
<i> and "Who farted? All the cows</i>
<i> raised by the beef industry!"</i>

12:40.576 --> 12:41.742
That's despicable.

12:41.820 --> 12:43.836
Though that fart slogan
makes a good point.

12:43.930 --> 12:46.598
You're pitting people
against each other.

12:46.825 --> 12:50.584
Lisa, that's what the T-shirt
industry has always done,

12:50.678 --> 12:52.512
ever since "I'm With Stupid."

12:52.664 --> 12:56.516
Now, Daddy's just giving
"stupid" a chance to respond.

12:56.610 --> 12:57.667
(phone rings)

12:57.760 --> 12:58.943
Ooh!
They're responding.

12:59.187 --> 13:02.596
Tell me who you hate and
I'll get it right out to you.

13:02.690 --> 13:04.699
♪ ♪

13:12.108 --> 13:14.367
Yeah, I-I just
want to say one thing

13:14.519 --> 13:17.036
to your millions
and millions of viewers:

13:17.188 --> 13:20.465
I'm being silenced!

13:23.194 --> 13:25.804
In all this discord,
if there's one thing

13:25.955 --> 13:29.349
that can bring us all together,
it's the holidays.

13:29.425 --> 13:31.868
I don't know.
The Christmas spirit

13:31.886 --> 13:33.728
just feels different this year.

13:34.722 --> 13:37.398
-Nice shirt.
-Go to hell.

13:38.726 --> 13:41.377
Stop the celebration!

13:41.396 --> 13:44.564
Oh, for the love of nog,
these loonies again?

13:44.658 --> 13:46.382
Yeah, and we won't stop looning

13:46.401 --> 13:50.328
until you stop teaching that
the gazebo was a disaster.

13:50.479 --> 13:52.071
But people died.

13:52.223 --> 13:54.907
That's why I'm an orphan.

13:55.060 --> 13:57.168
Oh, this guy's a crisis actor.

13:57.395 --> 13:59.412
How come every bad thing

13:59.564 --> 14:02.173
seems to conveniently
happen to him?

14:02.325 --> 14:05.343
-(screeches)
-Aah! Aah!

14:06.221 --> 14:08.996
We must never forget the gazebo,

14:09.090 --> 14:11.332
the victims
who lost their lives,

14:11.351 --> 14:14.744
and the suitors
who lost their ukuleles.

14:14.762 --> 14:16.079
Martin?

14:17.265 --> 14:21.084
♪<i> There's a story that goes</i>
